ref: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.66, p.044607 (2002)
title: Projectile dependence of radioactive spallation products induced in copper by high-energy heavy ions

x4freetext: Projectile dependence of radioactive spallation
products induced in copper by high-energy heavy ions

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.66, p.044607 (2002)

x4freetext: Department of quantum science and energy
engineering

x4codes.hlp: RIKEN (Inst. of Physical and Chemical Research), Wako, Japan
Nat.Inst. for Quantum & Radiol.Sci.& Tech., Chiba, Japan

x4freetext: -By authors.  Irradiation experiments were performed at
the HIMAC (heavy-ion medical accelerator) facility.
The radioactive spallation products in a thick  Cu
target were obtained for 230 and 100 MeV/nucleon Ne,
C, He, and H ions.  The gamma-ray spectra from
irradiated Cu pieces inserted into the composite Cu
target were measured with a high-purity Ge detector.
From the gamma-ray spectra, we obtained the variation
of radioactive yields with depth in the Cu target and
the mass-yield distribution of nuclides produced on the
surface.  The results show that the cross sections
strongly depend on the projectile mass and,
consequently, on the mass number difference between
Cu  and the produced nuclides.  The most important
feature of the present data is the extraction of the
energy dependence of the cross sections.  The measured
cross sections were fitted to a modified form
of Rudstam`s semiempirical formula in order to evaluate
the cross sections of unmeasured nuclides.  These
estimated cross sections were added to the experimental
yields for each mass number and the total mass yield
and isobaric charge distributions, and the slope of the
mass-yield distribution were obtained.
See reference

x4freetext: -By authors.  To order to compare the independent
yields derived from the measured cross sections with
the charge distribution, it is convenient to divide
both corrected experimental and calculated cross
sections by the calculated total isobar cross section
in order to obtain fractional isobar yields.  For the
purpose of better display and comparison with previous
results, the experimental values fractional isobar
yields are scaled to an arbitrary common mass
number A = 51 using the ratio of calculated fractional
isobar yield values at A = 51 and at the actual mass
number as a scaling factor.
- By compiler. The authors gave zero values for some
data-err. The values are meaningless. Therefore
compiler changed the values to empty DATA-ERR field.
Most probable charge of reaction product for
given mass. The value has been calculated by compiler
according to authors` formulae.
